{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17506602","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17506602"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:44:31+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:44:31+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2550"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2550","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2550"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.46,0.4,0.01,0.12,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2550"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"104907"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2550","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2550"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2550"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"87293"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"15"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1984"},{"type":"tags","id":"2960"},{"type":"tags","id":"4969"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2597"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2602"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13912"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18069"},{"type":"contributions","id":"37123"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43186"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"104907","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/104907"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 23-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a two-day history of fever, rash, and right flank pain. He was last seen by a physician nine days ago due to severe sore throat and painful swallowing, for which he was given a 10-day course of phenoxymethylpenicillin. He also has joint pains for which he is taking paracetamol. On examination, his blood pressure is 130/75 mmHg, pulse 99/min and temperature 38.1\u003Csup\u003Eo\u003C/sup\u003EC. He has a widespread maculopapular rash. Right costovertebral angle tenderness is present.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESerum creatinine: 192 \u00b5mol/L (60-110)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUrinalysis:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EProtein: Absent\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBlood: Present\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EGlucose: Absent\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELeukocyte esterase: Negative\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ENitrites: Negative\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBacteria: Absent\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhite blood cells (WBC): 20-30/high-power field (hpf)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ERed blood cells (RBC): 5-7/hpf\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECasts: WBC casts\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Acute tubulointerstitial nephritis","Acute glomerulonephritis","Nephrolithiasis","Acute pyelonephritis","Urothelial cancer"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient most likely has \u003Cstrong\u003Eacute tubulointerstitial nephritis\u003C/strong\u003E (ATIN). ATIN is a type IV hypersensitivity reaction that is often triggered by several medications (eg, penicillin, cephalosporins, NSAIDs, sulfonamides) within days to weeks of starting them. It may be asymptomatic. Symptomatic patients present with fever, maculopapular rash, flank pain, and arthralgia. This patient\u0027s recently prescribed penicillin drug for his pharyngitis is the most likely cause of his symptoms. Serum creatinine is usually elevated. Urinalysis typically reveals microscopic haematuria, pyuria, eosinophiluria, and WBC casts. The most appropriate management is the discontinuation of the offending medication.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHe does not have \u003Cstrong\u003Eacute glomerulonephritis\u003C/strong\u003E because of the lack of proteinuria or significant haematuria.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENephrolithiasis\u003C/strong\u003E presents with severe flank pain associated with nausea and vomiting. Haematuria may be seen. However, WBC casts and sterile pyuria are not seen.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAcute pyelonephritis\u003C/strong\u003E is usually associated with positive leukocyte esterase and bacteria on urinalysis. Nitrites may or may not be seen. This patient\u0027s urinalysis is negative for leukocyte esterase, nitrites, and bacteria.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUrothelial cancer\u003C/strong\u003E presents with gross haematuria. However, WBC casts and sterile pyuria are unlikely to be seen.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Acute tubulointerstitial nephritis is a hypersensitivity reaction, most often triggered by a medication."],"references":["Perazella MA, Markowitz GS. Drug-induced acute interstitial nephritis. Nat Rev Nephrol. 2010 Aug;6(8):461\u201370. Available from: https://www.nature.com/articles/nrneph.2010.71","Praga M, Gonz\u00e1lez E. Acute interstitial nephritis. Kidney International. 2010 Jun 1;77(11):956\u201361. Available from: https://www.kidney-international.org/article/S0085-2538(15)54176-8/fulltext"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"87293"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2550"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"87293","links":{"self":"